1
00:01:25,618 --> 00:01:28,109
[Yelling]

2
00:01:28,188 --> 00:01:30,179
Ho! Ho! Ho!

3
00:01:43,903 --> 00:01:47,031
[Woman Narrating] It's been almost ayear
since I left my home in the East...

4
00:01:47,107 --> 00:01:49,940
and traveled west
with the man I loved.

5
00:01:50,009 --> 00:01:52,170
I was positive
about my future...

6
00:01:52,245 --> 00:01:54,338
full of hopes and dreams.

7
00:01:54,414 --> 00:01:56,348
Our eyes were always
on the end of the trail...

8
00:01:56,416 --> 00:02:00,375
as if life as I envisioned it
would be just that.

9
00:02:00,453 --> 00:02:04,617
In fact, if someone had told me
that I would find myself here today...

10
00:02:04,691 --> 00:02:06,921
I would have
called them crazy.

11
00:02:06,993 --> 00:02:10,224
I was sure of myself
and where I was headed...

12
00:02:10,296 --> 00:02:13,390
stubborn and full of pride.

13
00:02:13,466 --> 00:02:15,434
I was in control.

14
00:02:15,502 --> 00:02:17,493
Or so I thought.

15
00:02:17,570 --> 00:02:20,266
Quit acting like a kid, Marty.
Get back here.

16
00:02:20,340 --> 00:02:24,276
No. Not until you admit
that I am right and head this way.

17
00:02:24,344 --> 00:02:27,279
- We're going in the right direction.
- We're going north.

18
00:02:27,347 --> 00:02:29,212
Mr. Graham said
to go north.

19
00:02:29,282 --> 00:02:31,580
He said to go northwest.

20
00:02:31,651 --> 00:02:35,451
Don't you think it's strange
we haven't come upon it yet?

21
00:02:35,522 --> 00:02:40,755
Well, we'd be there already if the weight
of these books hadn't slowed us down.

22
00:02:40,827 --> 00:02:44,263
Those books will provide us
with a little culture once we get settled.

23
00:02:44,330 --> 00:02:46,696
- It's too bad we can't eat any of that culture.
- [Groans]

24
00:02:46,766 --> 00:02:48,700
That 200 pounds
of beans and rice...

25
00:02:48,768 --> 00:02:50,998
that we had to toss off the wagon
to lessen the weight...

26
00:02:51,070 --> 00:02:54,699
would taste a whole lot better right now
than the 200 pounds of books we got!

27
00:02:54,774 --> 00:02:58,107
None of this would have happened
if you hadn't talked me into coming out here...

28
00:02:58,178 --> 00:03:00,772
to the middle of nowhere,
Aaron Claridge!

29
00:03:00,847 --> 00:03:05,409
We both know that
you don't do anything you don't want to do.

30
00:03:08,154 --> 00:03:10,884
For once in your life,
be reasonable.

31
00:03:10,957 --> 00:03:13,152
I'm tired...

32
00:03:13,226 --> 00:03:15,990
sick and tired
of the dirt...

33
00:03:16,062 --> 00:03:18,360
and miles that seem to
lead nowhere...

34
00:03:18,431 --> 00:03:20,991
and the layers
of dust on my skin...

35
00:03:21,067 --> 00:03:23,035
aching feet, aching back.

36
00:03:23,102 --> 00:03:26,367
If I never sit in that wagon again,
it'll be all right by me.

37
00:03:31,444 --> 00:03:33,435
Marty.

38
00:03:35,281 --> 00:03:37,272
I see.

39
00:04:01,574 --> 00:04:04,008
It's exactly
like I pictured.

40
00:04:06,346 --> 00:04:08,541
Can you see it?
Just over there.

41
00:04:08,615 --> 00:04:11,209
A cabin, with curtains
in the windows.

42
00:04:11,284 --> 00:04:13,775
A-A-And over here,
a barn.

43
00:04:13,853 --> 00:04:16,845
And a garden where we'll grow
our own food.

44
00:04:16,923 --> 00:04:18,891
Those trees are just
made for swings...

45
00:04:18,958 --> 00:04:21,722
for all those kids who are gonna look
just like their mama.

46
00:04:21,794 --> 00:04:25,059
I don't mind if they look like their father.

47
00:04:25,131 --> 00:04:27,429
We did it.
[Laughs]

48
00:04:27,500 --> 00:04:29,593
We actually did it, Marty.

49
00:04:29,669 --> 00:04:31,637
This just feels right,
doesn't it?

50
00:04:31,704 --> 00:04:33,729
This will be the perfect place
to raise a family.

51
00:04:33,806 --> 00:04:35,740
Pass down the land
to our children...

52
00:04:35,808 --> 00:04:37,742
and give them opportunities
that are limitless.

53
00:04:39,545 --> 00:04:42,412
We can do anything
as long as we're together.

54
00:04:54,260 --> 00:04:57,718
[Both Laughing]

55
00:04:57,797 --> 00:04:59,924
Promise me...

56
00:04:59,999 --> 00:05:02,126
that even if
things get rough...

57
00:05:02,201 --> 00:05:04,829
we'll remind each
other of that, okay?

58
00:05:04,904 --> 00:05:06,895
I promise.

59
00:05:15,782 --> 00:05:17,773
[Aaron]
Dad blame it.

60
00:05:18,818 --> 00:05:20,877
Marty.

61
00:05:22,422 --> 00:05:24,356
One of the horses got away.

62
00:05:24,424 --> 00:05:27,951
- Oh, no, Aaron.
- I'm taking the other horse,
and I'm going after him.

63
00:05:28,027 --> 00:05:31,690
Shouldn't be gone too long.
He's probably just a ways downstream.

64
00:05:37,270 --> 00:05:39,261
I'm coming with you.

65
00:05:39,339 --> 00:05:43,139
No need. I'll be back
with the horse before breakfast.

66
00:05:43,209 --> 00:05:46,269
Make up a lot of pancakes.
I'll be hungry.

67
00:06:08,735 --> 00:06:11,670
- [Whinny]
- Got ya.

68
00:06:11,738 --> 00:06:13,467
[Whinnies]

69
00:06:13,539 --> 00:06:15,097
Hyah!

70
00:06:18,845 --> 00:06:20,836
Come on!

71
00:06:25,251 --> 00:06:27,276
Hyah! Come on!
Let's go!

72
00:06:35,495 --> 00:06:37,429
Hyah!

73
00:06:37,497 --> 00:06:41,160
Come on.
Come on. Let's go.

74
00:06:46,272 --> 00:06:48,263
Hyah! Hyah!

75
00:06:50,943 --> 00:06:53,673
[Whinnies]

76
00:07:43,796 --> 00:07:45,821
[Aaron's Voice]
Marty.

77
00:08:06,185 --> 00:08:08,176
[Horse Whinnies]

78
00:08:35,014 --> 00:08:37,005
Whoa. Whoa.

79
00:08:42,722 --> 00:08:45,350
Miss Claridge.
Ben.

80
00:08:45,424 --> 00:08:48,222
Ben Graham, ma'am.
Met you a couple days back.

81
00:08:55,001 --> 00:08:57,731
Found him
about an hour ago.

82
00:09:42,582 --> 00:09:45,107
Miss Claridge.

83
00:09:45,184 --> 00:09:48,210
Can I get you
some water? Ma'am?

84
00:09:52,291 --> 00:09:54,282
[Muffled Sobs]

85
00:09:55,928 --> 00:09:57,919
Miss Claridge?

86
00:10:01,400 --> 00:10:03,800
Well, I guess you'll be
needing time to...

87
00:10:03,869 --> 00:10:05,803
to think, uh...

88
00:10:05,871 --> 00:10:08,533
My wife will see to
your husband.

89
00:10:08,608 --> 00:10:11,577
The preacher's leaving
tomorrow.

90
00:10:11,644 --> 00:10:14,135
I can bring him back here
first thing in the morning...

91
00:10:14,213 --> 00:10:16,704
to say a few words.

92
00:10:21,153 --> 00:10:23,144
Oh.

93
00:10:30,596 --> 00:10:32,723
[MartyWhispering]
We're fine.

94
00:10:34,300 --> 00:10:37,133
We're fine.

95
00:10:37,203 --> 00:10:39,171
We're fine.

96
00:10:40,740 --> 00:10:43,538
We're fine.

97
00:10:43,609 --> 00:10:46,134
- We're fine.
- [Coyote Howling In Distance]

98
00:10:49,348 --> 00:10:51,441
We're fine.

99
00:10:55,021 --> 00:10:57,080
[Woman Clears Throat]
Hello?

100
00:10:58,658 --> 00:11:00,649
Mrs. Claridge?

101
00:11:01,861 --> 00:11:03,852
Marty?

102
00:11:03,929 --> 00:11:05,920
It's me.

103
00:11:05,998 --> 00:11:08,432
Sarah Graham,
Ben's wife.

104
00:11:08,501 --> 00:11:10,992
You met me
a couple days ago.

105
00:11:16,442 --> 00:11:18,433
Marty...

106
00:11:20,112 --> 00:11:22,706
it's time.

107
00:11:22,782 --> 00:11:26,183
We need to start
your husband's funeral.

108
00:11:26,252 --> 00:11:28,618
We don't want to be
starting it without ya.

109
00:11:56,882 --> 00:11:59,112
I can't do this.

110
00:12:04,090 --> 00:12:06,081
You have to do this.

111
00:12:10,062 --> 00:12:12,292
[Whispering]
I would...

112
00:12:12,364 --> 00:12:15,731
I would appreciate just...
just a moment, please.

113
00:12:18,304 --> 00:12:20,295
We'll wait.

114
00:12:32,218 --> 00:12:34,584
[Sobs]

115
00:12:50,803 --> 00:12:56,571
[Man] Aaron Claridge journeyed west
in search of a dream.

116
00:12:56,642 --> 00:13:00,373
His untimely death means
that one journey is over.

117
00:13:00,446 --> 00:13:02,710
Another has just begun.

118
00:13:11,557 --> 00:13:13,548
[Sighs]

119
00:13:20,432 --> 00:13:24,368
[Sarah] Winter is coming, and there's
no wagon train heading east till spring.

120
00:13:26,172 --> 00:13:29,505
I don't know how you're fixed for money
to board in town, but...

121
00:13:30,843 --> 00:13:34,074
you're gonna have to make
a decision... and soon.

122
00:13:36,315 --> 00:13:39,375
[Sighs]
Well...

123
00:13:39,451 --> 00:13:42,614
you take tonight
and think on it, and...

124
00:13:42,688 --> 00:13:44,883
Ben'll come
and check on you tomorrow.

125
00:13:46,058 --> 00:13:48,049
Thankyou.

126
00:14:10,349 --> 00:14:12,749
[ThunderRumbling]

127
00:14:30,069 --> 00:14:31,559
Excuse me, ma'am.

128
00:14:33,839 --> 00:14:36,000
I'm Clark Davis...

129
00:14:36,075 --> 00:14:38,236
and I'm truly sorry
about your loss.

130
00:14:42,481 --> 00:14:44,472
I have a proposition for you.

131
00:14:51,323 --> 00:14:54,815
I know it's not the right place
or the right time.

132
00:14:55,995 --> 00:14:57,986
[ThunderRumbling]

133
00:14:58,063 --> 00:15:00,190
But I figure if we marry...

134
00:15:00,266 --> 00:15:02,291
it'll help solve
both our problems.

135
00:15:02,368 --> 00:15:04,768
You'll have a roof
over your head...

136
00:15:04,837 --> 00:15:07,032
and all your needs
will be met...

137
00:15:07,106 --> 00:15:10,542
and my Missie,
well, she'll have a mama.

138
00:15:10,609 --> 00:15:14,409
I know it sounds crazy...

139
00:15:14,480 --> 00:15:17,745
and the timing is unlikely...

140
00:15:17,816 --> 00:15:21,115
but you have to understand
the preacher's leaving the area today...

141
00:15:21,186 --> 00:15:23,154
and he's not gonna be back
until spring...

142
00:15:24,590 --> 00:15:27,423
and I ask this
only for my daughter.

143
00:15:28,928 --> 00:15:30,919
I'm thinking...

144
00:15:32,231 --> 00:15:37,794
that she needs a woman's hand
in parts ofher life.

145
00:15:37,870 --> 00:15:40,964
I know it's not
the perfect solution...

146
00:15:41,040 --> 00:15:44,134
but when the wagon train
heads back east in the spring...

147
00:15:47,613 --> 00:15:49,706
I'll pay the passage
so you can go home.

148
00:15:52,985 --> 00:15:54,976
You'll help me get home?

149
00:15:55,054 --> 00:15:57,045
If that's what you want.

150
00:16:00,793 --> 00:16:03,159
I'll leave you
to think on it, ma'am.

151
00:16:27,686 --> 00:16:29,677
[Child]
Get her off of ya!

152
00:16:29,755 --> 00:16:31,222
[All Shouting]

153
00:16:31,290 --> 00:16:34,919
So I had to be chasing after 'em.
The next thing... Hey!

154
00:16:34,994 --> 00:16:37,428
- I tried to stop them.
- [Ben] Hey! Hey!

155
00:16:37,496 --> 00:16:39,487
- [Grunting]
- Missie.

156
00:16:39,565 --> 00:16:41,624
Hey, hey.
Come here.

157
00:16:43,035 --> 00:16:45,265
[Panting]
He started it, Pa.

158
00:16:45,337 --> 00:16:46,861
You get up.
Get up!

159
00:16:46,939 --> 00:16:50,534
Clint says I got a new ma.
He's lying to me.

160
00:16:50,609 --> 00:16:53,043
- Is that true, Clint?
- No, sir.

161
00:16:53,112 --> 00:16:55,740
She poked me right in the nose
for no good reason.

162
00:16:55,814 --> 00:16:58,612
You're a liar.
That is so a good reason.

163
00:16:58,684 --> 00:17:02,211
[Clark]
Hey. Where do you think you're going?

164
00:17:02,287 --> 00:17:04,221
Apologize.

165
00:17:04,289 --> 00:17:06,257
[Panting]

166
00:17:06,325 --> 00:17:08,316
Sorry.

167
00:17:11,497 --> 00:17:14,159
Sorry.

168
00:17:14,233 --> 00:17:16,895
What'd I tell you about fighting with girls?

169
00:17:16,969 --> 00:17:20,097
I ain't fighting with no girl.
It's just Missie.

170
00:17:21,407 --> 00:17:23,466
Get inside.
Go on.

171
00:17:23,542 --> 00:17:25,976
- No worries.
- Come on, Missie.

172
00:17:26,979 --> 00:17:28,970
We need to talk.

173
00:17:32,618 --> 00:17:35,678
[Indistinct]

174
00:17:35,754 --> 00:17:38,222
Oh, God,
I don't want to do this.

175
00:17:38,290 --> 00:17:41,259
- I just wanna go home.
- Now you listen to me.

176
00:17:42,895 --> 00:17:45,489
There is no place
in this part of the county...

177
00:17:45,564 --> 00:17:49,022
to waste your time
cying overwants.

178
00:17:49,101 --> 00:17:51,535
Your life's
about needs now.

179
00:17:51,603 --> 00:17:55,630
You need a roof overyour head
for the winter.

180
00:17:55,707 --> 00:17:58,870
That's what
you bargained for.

181
00:17:58,944 --> 00:18:01,674
We are here today,
gathered in the Lord's name...

182
00:18:01,747 --> 00:18:04,215
to join this man
and this woman in marriage.

183
00:18:04,283 --> 00:18:06,547
Please join hands.

184
00:18:12,591 --> 00:18:17,494
Will you, Clark Davis, take Marty Claridge
to be your lawful wedded wife?

185
00:18:17,563 --> 00:18:19,497
I will.

186
00:18:22,701 --> 00:18:24,635
And will you,
Marty Claridge...

187
00:18:24,703 --> 00:18:27,968
take Clark Davis
to be your husband?

188
00:18:31,276 --> 00:18:34,040
Come on now. Let's go.

189
00:18:36,748 --> 00:18:38,807
Just answer, "I will."

190
00:18:38,884 --> 00:18:41,478
I will.

191
00:18:42,654 --> 00:18:45,020
Then I pronounce you
man and wife.

192
00:19:05,310 --> 00:19:07,710
[Dog Barking]

193
00:19:07,779 --> 00:19:09,838
[Missie]
Buddy. Come here, Buddy.

194
00:19:09,915 --> 00:19:11,906
I'll bring in your trunk.

195
00:19:27,599 --> 00:19:30,693
[Clears Throat]
This is the bedroom you and Missie will be sharing.

196
00:19:30,769 --> 00:19:32,760
I'll get my things moved
into the lean-to.

197
00:20:22,754 --> 00:20:24,813
[Owl Hooting]

198
00:20:50,716 --> 00:20:52,650
[Plates Clinking]

199
00:20:59,524 --> 00:21:01,515
[Door Opens]

200
00:21:04,162 --> 00:21:06,153
Good mornin'.
[Clears Throat]

201
00:21:07,899 --> 00:21:10,299
Saved you some ham. I'm...

202
00:21:10,369 --> 00:21:14,237
I'm not much of a cook,
but it's usually pretty fillin'.

203
00:21:16,441 --> 00:21:19,103
I've never seen
nobody sleep so long.

204
00:21:19,177 --> 00:21:21,168
I thought you might be dead.

205
00:21:21,246 --> 00:21:22,679
[Clark]
Missie.

206
00:21:22,748 --> 00:21:25,512
Go and wait for me
in the wagon.

207
00:21:27,552 --> 00:21:30,282
- [Footsteps Departing]
- [Sighs]

208
00:21:32,291 --> 00:21:34,350
Got some things
I need to tend to.

209
00:21:34,426 --> 00:21:36,621
I'll be taking
Missie with me.

210
00:21:36,695 --> 00:21:38,686
[Clears Throat]

211
00:21:39,698 --> 00:21:41,666
Won't be back till supper.

212
00:21:44,436 --> 00:21:46,927
Ma'am.

213
00:21:56,782 --> 00:21:58,773
[Wagon Departing]

214
00:22:43,061 --> 00:22:44,995
[Weeping]

215
00:23:10,756 --> 00:23:12,690
[Sobbing]

216
00:23:24,770 --> 00:23:26,704
[Door Opens]

217
00:23:26,772 --> 00:23:28,831
[Footsteps Approaching]

218
00:23:29,975 --> 00:23:33,911
- She's sleeping again.
- Mm-hmm.

219
00:23:33,979 --> 00:23:35,970
[Whispering]
Let's go have our supper.

220
00:23:36,047 --> 00:23:39,539
Pa, is she all right?

221
00:23:39,618 --> 00:23:41,609
No.

222
00:23:42,687 --> 00:23:44,678
But she will be.

223
00:23:46,725 --> 00:23:48,716
Come on.

224
00:23:57,269 --> 00:23:59,669
- [Horse Whinnies]
- [Gasps]

225
00:23:59,738 --> 00:24:02,172
[Panting]

226
00:24:07,078 --> 00:24:09,308
[Horse Whinnies]

227
00:24:14,553 --> 00:24:17,044
- [Clark] Come on. Come on.
- [Whinnies]

228
00:24:17,122 --> 00:24:19,113
Come on.

229
00:24:28,333 --> 00:24:32,064
And bless this dear child
in her time of grief...

230
00:24:32,137 --> 00:24:36,403
and bless this food before us, and we thank you
for the fine day ahead of us.

231
00:24:36,475 --> 00:24:38,466
Amen.

232
00:24:49,187 --> 00:24:51,678
You got an awful lot
of pretty dresses.

233
00:24:55,627 --> 00:24:59,028
You got an awful lot of fancy things
that aren't good for much anythin' at all...

234
00:24:59,097 --> 00:25:01,565
We fetched your wagon yesterday
and brought it into the barn.

235
00:25:03,768 --> 00:25:07,101
What are you gonna do
with all them books?

236
00:25:14,446 --> 00:25:18,883
I checked to see if there was any food that was
spoiled when I was picking up your things.

237
00:25:18,950 --> 00:25:22,249
We planned on buying supplies
as soon as we found our land.

238
00:25:22,320 --> 00:25:24,720
Books must be
pretty important toya.

239
00:25:24,789 --> 00:25:27,917
I'll see if we can
find space for 'em in the cabin.

240
00:25:29,794 --> 00:25:33,161
I'm not sure what you're
expecting from me.

241
00:25:34,165 --> 00:25:36,133
Come with me.

242
00:25:40,672 --> 00:25:42,606
Missie's nine years old.

243
00:25:42,674 --> 00:25:46,303
She works almost as hard as I do,
sunup to sundown.

244
00:25:46,378 --> 00:25:49,074
Has been for the last
couple of years.

245
00:25:49,147 --> 00:25:51,138
She never complains...

246
00:25:52,317 --> 00:25:55,013
but the work is stealing
her childhood.

247
00:25:55,086 --> 00:25:57,179
She doesn't know
what she's missin'...

248
00:25:59,291 --> 00:26:01,282
but I do.

249
00:26:01,359 --> 00:26:06,353
Maybe if somebody's there
to share the chores...

250
00:26:06,431 --> 00:26:08,626
she'd have time to learn...

251
00:26:08,700 --> 00:26:11,828
some of the things
I think you could teach her.

252
00:26:14,806 --> 00:26:17,536
Things she'd learn
from her mother.

253
00:26:17,609 --> 00:26:20,840
And when I go home
in the spring?

254
00:26:23,782 --> 00:26:26,683
I figure I'll cross that bridge
when I come to it.

255
00:26:29,888 --> 00:26:31,879
The books.

256
00:26:31,957 --> 00:26:35,791
How did you know they were mine and...
and not Aaron's?

257
00:26:35,860 --> 00:26:40,263
Oh, well, a man would have
thrown them offthe wagon at the first big hill...

258
00:26:40,332 --> 00:26:43,130
unless he was tying to please
a stubborn woman.

259
00:26:48,607 --> 00:26:50,541
[Chickens Clucking]

260
00:26:54,479 --> 00:26:56,470
Why areyou here?

261
00:26:56,548 --> 00:26:58,675
[Sighs]

262
00:26:58,750 --> 00:27:00,775
I thought you could use
some help.

263
00:27:00,852 --> 00:27:02,877
What would you
like me to do?

264
00:27:02,954 --> 00:27:06,913
You may need a place to stay, but I don't need
a mother. Pa and me been doin' fine.

265
00:27:10,562 --> 00:27:12,655
I'm a little unsure
about what to do.

266
00:27:14,499 --> 00:27:18,458
Why don't you show me how to
get those eggs out from underneath their...

267
00:27:18,536 --> 00:27:20,504
you know.

268
00:27:20,572 --> 00:27:22,563
Their rears?

269
00:27:23,875 --> 00:27:25,866
[Sighs]

270
00:27:29,648 --> 00:27:31,616
[Marty]
Spell "cow. '"

271
00:27:31,683 --> 00:27:34,743
K-A...

272
00:27:34,819 --> 00:27:36,946
Close. It's C-O-W.

273
00:27:37,022 --> 00:27:39,752
Gertie don't care
if I know how to spell "cow" or not.

274
00:27:39,824 --> 00:27:41,758
Gertie doesn't care...

275
00:27:41,826 --> 00:27:43,794
but I do
and so does your pa.

276
00:27:43,862 --> 00:27:45,887
So let's try another one.

277
00:27:45,964 --> 00:27:48,398
Spell "fun."

278
00:27:48,466 --> 00:27:50,457
F...

279
00:27:50,535 --> 00:27:52,059
[Moos]

280
00:27:54,172 --> 00:27:57,733
- How do you spell "warm"?
- Warm? W-A-R-M.

281
00:27:57,809 --> 00:28:00,607
I think you better
W-A-R-M your hands.

282
00:28:00,679 --> 00:28:03,842
- What?
- Well, how do you expect Gertie
to give you good milk...

283
00:28:03,915 --> 00:28:05,906
when you're freezing her
like that?

284
00:28:05,984 --> 00:28:07,975
Probably spell "milking. '"

285
00:28:08,053 --> 00:28:10,817
[Whispers]
Sure can't do it.

286
00:28:10,889 --> 00:28:13,756
[Groans]

287
00:28:20,198 --> 00:28:23,725
How'd you get to be so old
without not knowin' how to do nothin'?

288
00:28:27,839 --> 00:28:30,000
[Squeaking]

289
00:28:30,075 --> 00:28:32,066
[Marty Panting]

290
00:28:50,829 --> 00:28:53,093
- [Marty Grunts]
- [WaterSloshing]

291
00:29:00,205 --> 00:29:02,503
[Gasps]

292
00:29:03,608 --> 00:29:04,870
[Grunts]

293
00:29:06,144 --> 00:29:08,874
Oops. I really didn't mean to.

294
00:29:08,947 --> 00:29:13,281
I know exactly what you're meaning to do,
Missie. Now you listen to me.

295
00:29:13,351 --> 00:29:15,842
You're not my mother,
and I don't have to listen toyou.

296
00:29:15,920 --> 00:29:18,013
- As long as I am here...
- I don't want you here.

297
00:29:18,089 --> 00:29:20,853
I've got news for you!
I don't want to be here either...

298
00:29:20,925 --> 00:29:23,917
but the fact of the matter is
I made a bargain with your father...

299
00:29:23,995 --> 00:29:26,122
and I intend to keep
my end of that bargain...

300
00:29:26,197 --> 00:29:29,189
even if you do everything
short of trying to kill me in the process.

301
00:29:30,435 --> 00:29:32,369
So the way I see it...

302
00:29:32,437 --> 00:29:35,964
if I can survive traveling for months
in a covered wagon...

303
00:29:36,040 --> 00:29:38,804
losing my husband,
marrying a complete stranger...

304
00:29:38,877 --> 00:29:41,744
I can survive you.
[Exhales]

305
00:29:45,416 --> 00:29:47,350
So how was your day?

306
00:29:47,418 --> 00:29:49,545
- Fine.
- Yeah, fine.

307
00:29:51,322 --> 00:29:53,313
[Clears Throat]

308
00:29:53,391 --> 00:29:57,987
I ran into Ben and Sarah Graham in town today,
and they were asking after you.

309
00:29:58,062 --> 00:29:59,996
That was kind of them.

310
00:30:00,064 --> 00:30:03,397
Actually, they invited us all
to their annual get-together.

311
00:30:03,468 --> 00:30:05,959
- Is it already time?
- It is.

312
00:30:06,037 --> 00:30:10,064
You see, the Grahams have a party,
uh, this time of year...

313
00:30:10,141 --> 00:30:14,305
so all the folks can get together
before we're stuck inside for the winter.

314
00:30:18,016 --> 00:30:21,179
We'd understand it if, you know,
you weren't up for a party...

315
00:30:21,252 --> 00:30:23,447
but it's up to you.

316
00:30:23,521 --> 00:30:27,013
You probably wouldn't like it.
There's tons of people you won't know.

317
00:30:27,091 --> 00:30:29,184
You'd probably just like
staying home better...

318
00:30:29,260 --> 00:30:31,854
- don't you think, Pa?
- I think I will go.

319
00:30:33,665 --> 00:30:35,064
Good.

320
00:30:40,772 --> 00:30:42,763
[Soft Knocking On Door]

321
00:30:45,310 --> 00:30:48,040
- What is it?
- I just need to talk to you.

322
00:30:49,647 --> 00:30:52,309
Missie's asleep, and I'm ready for bed.
Can't we talk tomorrow?

323
00:30:52,383 --> 00:30:55,546
Well, that's just it.
I won't be here tomorrow.

324
00:30:55,620 --> 00:30:58,145
I'm, uh... I'm leaving
before sunup.

325
00:30:58,223 --> 00:31:01,386
- I'm gonna help our neighbor.
- Fine.

326
00:31:01,459 --> 00:31:03,290
W-Wait. It...

327
00:31:03,361 --> 00:31:05,226
What else?

328
00:31:06,798 --> 00:31:08,823
I'll be leaving Missie
here with you.

329
00:31:08,900 --> 00:31:10,891
That is why I'm here.

330
00:31:10,969 --> 00:31:13,164
Yeah, I... You know...

331
00:31:13,238 --> 00:31:16,173
I just wasn't sure if you were
up to dealing with a spirited...

332
00:31:16,241 --> 00:31:18,266
I'm fine.
Something else?

333
00:31:18,343 --> 00:31:22,177
No. Ye...
I'll be back by supper.

334
00:31:22,247 --> 00:31:25,648
- Fine. Good night.
- Good... night.

335
00:31:33,191 --> 00:31:35,182
[Sighs]
Missie.

336
00:31:45,136 --> 00:31:47,127
Missie!

337
00:31:48,840 --> 00:31:51,604
Missie, answer me.
Where are you?

338
00:31:51,676 --> 00:31:54,144
Missie?

339
00:32:01,352 --> 00:32:02,649
Missie!

340
00:32:04,555 --> 00:32:06,546
You better get out of here.

341
00:32:06,624 --> 00:32:10,720
[Sighs]
Why don'tyou come down so we can get to work?

342
00:32:10,795 --> 00:32:13,320
Okay.

343
00:32:13,398 --> 00:32:15,389
Just as soon as he leaves.

344
00:32:15,466 --> 00:32:16,626
He?

345
00:32:18,569 --> 00:32:20,298
[Gasps]

346
00:32:24,242 --> 00:32:26,676
Just come down slowly.

347
00:32:26,744 --> 00:32:30,077
I've read that they won't spray
unless they feel threatened.

348
00:32:30,148 --> 00:32:32,139
You read that
in one of your books?

349
00:32:32,216 --> 00:32:34,650
Uh-huh.

350
00:32:34,719 --> 00:32:38,052
- And you believe it?
- I do.

351
00:32:38,122 --> 00:32:40,590
Well, not me.

352
00:32:40,658 --> 00:32:44,651
I'm starving, and I gotta use
that outhouse something fierce...

353
00:32:44,729 --> 00:32:47,220
- but I'm not coming down.
- [Dog Barks]

354
00:32:47,298 --> 00:32:48,731
Buddy, no!

355
00:32:49,467 --> 00:32:52,095
[Screams]

356
00:32:52,170 --> 00:32:53,831
[Whimpers]

357
00:32:53,905 --> 00:32:55,532
[Coughs]

358
00:32:57,175 --> 00:32:59,109
[Marty Groaning]

359
00:32:59,177 --> 00:33:01,941
Guess he felt threatened.

360
00:33:03,014 --> 00:33:05,005
[Groans]

361
00:33:08,953 --> 00:33:10,944
[Groans]

362
00:33:12,290 --> 00:33:15,851
Are you sure this is going to take
the smell away?

363
00:33:15,927 --> 00:33:19,294
More or less.
Some of it's just gonna have to wear off.

364
00:33:19,364 --> 00:33:21,628
[Groans]

365
00:33:25,370 --> 00:33:28,464
[Coyote Howling]

366
00:33:28,539 --> 00:33:31,269
- The fire's dyin'.
- Could you?

367
00:33:31,342 --> 00:33:33,776
I ain't supposed to.
I could burn myself.

368
00:33:33,845 --> 00:33:35,779
[Sighs]

369
00:33:40,051 --> 00:33:42,042
Something's burnin'.

370
00:33:43,654 --> 00:33:45,645
Oh, no.

371
00:33:47,058 --> 00:33:49,049
Oh!

372
00:33:50,461 --> 00:33:52,656
[Marty]
Oh, dad blame it!

373
00:33:52,730 --> 00:33:54,994
- Ouch!
- Let me help you. Hold on.

374
00:33:55,066 --> 00:33:57,762
Hold on, hold on.
Missie, get me some butter, would ya?

375
00:33:57,835 --> 00:33:59,826
- Come on. Sit down.
- [Marty] It's fine.

376
00:33:59,904 --> 00:34:02,566
No, you sit down here.
I'm gonna wrap it up now.

377
00:34:02,640 --> 00:34:06,406
- [Marty Groans]
- [Sighs] Here.

378
00:34:06,477 --> 00:34:08,570
Thank you.

379
00:34:08,646 --> 00:34:10,341
It's nothing, really.

380
00:34:10,415 --> 00:34:15,011
Okay. Now this will just
take some ofthe sting out.

381
00:34:15,086 --> 00:34:18,249
- [Sighs]
- Pancakes are all burned.

382
00:34:18,322 --> 00:34:21,621
Here you go.
Like that.

383
00:34:21,692 --> 00:34:26,129
You know, you'll get the hang of that stove.
It just takes a little practice. That's all.

384
00:34:26,197 --> 00:34:29,428
- [Sighs]
- [Clears Throat]

385
00:34:29,500 --> 00:34:31,491
So where'd the skunk
find you?

386
00:34:32,770 --> 00:34:35,466
The barn.

387
00:34:35,540 --> 00:34:37,599
Better get
some more tomatoes, Pa.

388
00:34:37,675 --> 00:34:40,337
Took almost a whole bushel
to get her smelling this good.

389
00:34:42,847 --> 00:34:45,611
Well, I'll see what we've got
for supper in the icebox.

390
00:34:47,051 --> 00:34:49,815
Missie, why don'tyou go ahead
and stoke that fire?

391
00:34:49,887 --> 00:34:52,219
[DoorCloses]

392
00:34:59,363 --> 00:35:03,459
I'll ty to get all the things on your list
foryou while I'm in town.

393
00:35:03,534 --> 00:35:06,059
[Clears Throat]
You sure you don't want to go with us?

394
00:35:06,137 --> 00:35:08,605
No.

395
00:35:08,673 --> 00:35:11,301
She said she don't.

396
00:35:11,375 --> 00:35:13,343
Doesn't.

397
00:35:15,446 --> 00:35:18,882
Hope you can make something better
than burned pancakes.

398
00:35:18,950 --> 00:35:22,249
Too bad I'll be gone,
'cause I can make some real good fried chicken.

399
00:35:22,320 --> 00:35:24,185
I'm ready, Pa.

400
00:35:24,255 --> 00:35:26,246
Mm-hmm.

401
00:35:31,229 --> 00:35:34,221
We'll see ya soon.
Tsk, tsk.

402
00:35:38,603 --> 00:35:40,594
How hard can it be?

403
00:35:47,845 --> 00:35:49,836
[Sighs]

404
00:35:52,083 --> 00:35:55,416
If a child can do this,
I can do this.

405
00:35:57,054 --> 00:35:58,988
[Chickens Clucking]

406
00:36:00,858 --> 00:36:03,759
Come here, chickie.
Come here.

407
00:36:05,930 --> 00:36:07,454
[Grunts]

408
00:36:10,334 --> 00:36:12,234
Come here!

409
00:36:12,303 --> 00:36:14,498
Come here!
Dad blame it!

410
00:36:19,710 --> 00:36:21,644
[Panting]

411
00:36:24,982 --> 00:36:27,473
[Grunting]

412
00:36:31,689 --> 00:36:34,624
[Chicken Clucking]

413
00:36:46,337 --> 00:36:48,805
"Pull feathers out
with the grain."

414
00:36:51,175 --> 00:36:53,166
You better be worth it.

415
00:36:59,383 --> 00:37:01,374
Huh.

416
00:37:06,023 --> 00:37:08,856
Looks like a coyote
got in there.

417
00:37:08,926 --> 00:37:12,657
More like a wild woman
with an ax.

418
00:37:17,935 --> 00:37:20,699
Good. You're back.
Supper's ready.

419
00:37:20,771 --> 00:37:23,035
You made fried chicken.

420
00:37:23,107 --> 00:37:25,439
Good, 'cause I was
getting awful sick of panc...

421
00:37:25,509 --> 00:37:28,273
[Clears Throat]

422
00:37:28,346 --> 00:37:30,337
Me too.

423
00:37:36,854 --> 00:37:39,379
Sure won't want to
have to wash all that.

424
00:37:39,457 --> 00:37:41,550
I left half my things
at home.

425
00:37:41,626 --> 00:37:44,959
- It's kind of wasteful, don't you think?
- Wasteful?

426
00:37:45,029 --> 00:37:47,827
To have so many.
You can only wear one dress at a time.

427
00:37:47,898 --> 00:37:51,390
Surely you must have
some dresses of your own.

428
00:37:51,469 --> 00:37:55,064
One for when the reverend
passes this way and holds a service...

429
00:37:55,139 --> 00:37:57,664
but like I said,
you can only wear one dress...

430
00:37:57,742 --> 00:37:59,733
At a time.

431
00:38:03,648 --> 00:38:06,139
My mama made
beautiful quilts.

432
00:38:06,217 --> 00:38:08,515
Hers would put this here
pattern to shame.

433
00:38:10,454 --> 00:38:13,651
She made quilts for all the neighbors
when they had their babies.

434
00:38:13,724 --> 00:38:16,192
I'm sure
they appreciated that.

435
00:38:16,260 --> 00:38:19,718
Folks loved my mama,
especially my pa.

436
00:38:22,833 --> 00:38:26,234
That's why his eyes ain't sparkly
like they used to be.

437
00:38:28,105 --> 00:38:30,266
She certainly was beautiful.

438
00:38:30,341 --> 00:38:33,833
She was the prettiest
thing you ever saw.

439
00:38:33,911 --> 00:38:36,004
Eveybody said so.

440
00:38:39,183 --> 00:38:41,913
You must miss her
vey much.

441
00:39:23,594 --> 00:39:25,585
[Shivers]

442
00:39:29,700 --> 00:39:31,634
[Gasps]

443
00:39:31,702 --> 00:39:33,169
Oh, Lord.

444
00:39:33,237 --> 00:39:35,000
[Gasps]

445
00:39:35,072 --> 00:39:37,836
I'm sory.
[Screams]

446
00:39:37,908 --> 00:39:39,068
- [Gasps]
- Oh!

447
00:39:40,144 --> 00:39:41,771
[Groans]

448
00:39:44,515 --> 00:39:45,914
[Murmurs]

449
00:39:50,855 --> 00:39:52,846
[Murmuring]

450
00:40:06,137 --> 00:40:09,129
- Where's your father going?
- On his Sunday walks.

451
00:40:09,206 --> 00:40:11,834
It's his time to be alone
and talk to the Lord.

452
00:40:11,909 --> 00:40:14,605
I'll bet he has a lot
to talk to him about this morning.

453
00:40:14,678 --> 00:40:18,045
- What'd you say?
- I think I'll take a little walk of my own.

454
00:40:18,115 --> 00:40:20,413
Are you all right here
by yourself?

455
00:41:11,602 --> 00:41:14,730
[Missie] I picked this dress
because I know pink is your favorite color.

456
00:41:18,509 --> 00:41:21,171
I love it
when you wear pink, Mama.

457
00:41:21,245 --> 00:41:23,236
You always look so pretty.

458
00:41:29,687 --> 00:41:31,678
There.

459
00:41:31,755 --> 00:41:34,622
Letting in the sun
will make you feel better.

460
00:41:40,865 --> 00:41:43,834
[Sighs]

461
00:41:43,901 --> 00:41:47,962
L... I don't know why
they didn't let me come here, Mama.

462
00:41:48,038 --> 00:41:50,336
[Sighs]

463
00:41:50,407 --> 00:41:52,637
'Cause I would have sat here
just like this...

464
00:41:55,679 --> 00:42:00,707
and I wouldn't have
madeyou tired or sad.

465
00:42:02,520 --> 00:42:07,082
I just wanted to tell you
that I loveyou...

466
00:42:10,094 --> 00:42:12,756
and I miss you.

467
00:42:12,830 --> 00:42:14,457
[Sobs, Gasps]

468
00:42:21,138 --> 00:42:23,129
You were spying on me!

469
00:42:24,241 --> 00:42:26,835
- No.
- You're lyin'.

470
00:42:26,911 --> 00:42:30,312
I saw you. You were watching.
How could you do that?

471
00:42:30,381 --> 00:42:34,477
Missie, I didn't mean
to be there...

472
00:42:34,552 --> 00:42:36,577
but I do know
what you're feeling.

473
00:42:36,654 --> 00:42:39,487
Don't say that.
You don't know nothin'.

474
00:42:39,557 --> 00:42:41,650
I do want to help you.

475
00:42:41,725 --> 00:42:43,750
I don't want your help!

476
00:42:43,827 --> 00:42:45,988
I hate it that you're here.

477
00:42:46,063 --> 00:42:48,429
It was fine before you came.

478
00:42:48,499 --> 00:42:51,798
I wish it was spring
so you would leave.

479
00:43:16,694 --> 00:43:19,094
[Sighs]
I didn't mean to.

480
00:43:19,163 --> 00:43:22,655
I... I was cold. I... I didn't mean to
walk in on her like that.

481
00:43:22,733 --> 00:43:27,067
Well, I know what you mean.
About last night, l... I'm sorry.

482
00:43:27,137 --> 00:43:29,662
- I didn't mean to walk...
- I don't know what I was thinking.

483
00:43:29,740 --> 00:43:31,640
I can't stay here.

484
00:43:31,709 --> 00:43:35,668
- Why?
- Why? That little girl hates me.

485
00:43:35,746 --> 00:43:38,044
You were right.

486
00:43:38,115 --> 00:43:40,242
She does need a mother...

487
00:43:40,317 --> 00:43:42,308
but I'm not
the right person.

488
00:43:42,386 --> 00:43:45,480
She doesn't know it,
but she's still grieving.

489
00:43:45,556 --> 00:43:49,390
- That's why you're the right person.
- It's just not going well.

490
00:43:49,460 --> 00:43:51,519
It's going just the way
I thought it would.

491
00:43:51,595 --> 00:43:55,156
- I knew she wouldn't like it at first.
- Then why put her through this?

492
00:43:55,232 --> 00:43:57,291
Because I love her...

493
00:43:57,368 --> 00:43:59,336
and she needs more
than I can give her.

494
00:43:59,403 --> 00:44:01,701
Seems like an awful lot
oftrouble to go through...

495
00:44:01,772 --> 00:44:05,173
for just a few months of lessons
in letters and sewing.

496
00:44:05,242 --> 00:44:08,541
Nothing's a waste oftime.
It adds to the person that you are...

497
00:44:08,612 --> 00:44:10,546
and I'm counting
on the fact...

498
00:44:10,614 --> 00:44:14,573
that knowing you is gonna add to the person
that Missie will become.

499
00:44:14,652 --> 00:44:18,088
I know you can find a way
to get through to her.

500
00:44:20,024 --> 00:44:23,585
- How do you know?
- That's what I prayed for.

501
00:44:29,867 --> 00:44:32,199
[Sighs]

502
00:44:39,076 --> 00:44:41,067
Maybe I will.

503
00:46:06,363 --> 00:46:08,456
We're ready.

504
00:46:37,795 --> 00:46:40,320
You look beautiful, Missie.

505
00:46:42,833 --> 00:46:45,393
[Chuckles]
Thanks, Pa.

506
00:46:51,141 --> 00:46:53,075
